data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **bulk operations** — `ExecuteUpdateAsync` and `ExecuteDeleteAsync`. These translate directly to SQL `UPDATE`/`DELETE` statements without loading entities into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is fast:**
- No entities loaded into memory (0 objects tracked)
- Executes a single SQL statement server-side
- No `SaveChangesAsync()` needed — these execute immediately

**Caveats:**
- Bypasses change tracker — any already-loaded entities won't reflect the change
- No cascade deletes via EF navigation properties (DB-level cascades still work)
- If 2M deletes cause lock escalation/timeouts, batch with a loop:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
